<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901221-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>901221-0010.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>12/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   PRUDENTIAL-BACHE will post a $250 million loss for 1990,one of the worst performances ever by a U.S. brokerage firm.Its parent, Prudential Insurance, is adding more than $200million in new capital to bolster the sagging firm. The bigloss also raised new questions about how long George Ballwill remain as chairman of Prudential-Bache.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Merck disclosed that it developed a novel type of drug tofight the AIDS virus and that it began pilot tests of thedrug in humans last month.   ---   Rostenkowski said he no longer plans to reintroduce earlyin January a proposed surtax on millionaires. President Bush,meantime, said he won't include his twice-failed proposal tocut capital-gains taxes as part of his fiscal 1992 budgetrequest.   ---   The Big Board's new chairman, William Donaldson, wants togreatly expand the number of foreign stocks traded on theexchange. Mr. Donaldson will take office Jan. 1.   ---   The dollar surged against other major currencies amid agrowing threat of political instability in the Soviet Union.U.S. markets mostly shrugged off the developments.   ---   Sunbelt Savings' ex-owner, Edwin T. McBirney III, isexpected to plead guilty today to federal criminal charges,less than 24 hours after a jury convicted Don R. Dixon,ex-owner of Vernon Sandamp;L in Dallas.   ---   Bank of New England bondholders tentatively agreed to adebt-for-equity swap that would give them 92% of the ailingbank's common stock.                                                                                                          Bank of Boston said it will have a &quot;substantial loss&quot; inthe fourth quarter, ensuring a loss for the full year.   ---   BankAmerica plans to bid to acquire failed thrifts inTexas, New Mexico and California as part of its effort todominate retail banking in the West, company executives said.   ---   California's Supreme Court issued two rulings that couldlimit employees' ability to seek damages for emotionaldistress stemming from wrongful discharge. But another rulingaids employees in some cases.   ---   Consumer spending inched up 0.1% in November as incomesincreased only slightly, suggesting consumers won'tcontribute to economic strength in the next few months.   ---   Short interest showed little change on both the Big Boardand Amex in the month ended Dec. 14, after rising stronglyfor the past year.   ---   GE was selected to design the engine for Japan'scontroversial FSX fighter plane over United Technologies'Pratt andamp; Whitney division.   ---   Midwest manufacturers are feeling the pinch of the weakeconomy, largely due to auto industry cutbacks.   ---   Capital spending plans are being scaled back. In agovernment survey, businesses said they plan to raisespending a cautious 2.4% in 1991.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 174,700,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2629.46, up 2.73; transportation 915.67, off 1.31; utilities209.88, off 1.70.   Bonds: Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3666.55, off 20.41.   Commodities: Oil $26.39 a barrel, down 54 cents; Dow Jonesfutures index 126.51, up 0.10; spot index 123.97, up 0.62.   Dollar: 135.85 yen, up 1.80; 1.5115 marks, up 0.0330.</TEXT></DOC>